{"title_page": "Music of Albania", "text_new": "{{short description|Music coming from the country of Albania}}\n{{Culture of Albania}}{{Music of Albania}}\n\nThe '''Music of Albania''' ({{lang-sq|Muzika Shqiptare}}) is associated with the country of [[Albania]] and [[Albanian diaspora|Albanian communities]]. [[Music]] has a long tradition in the country and is known for its regional diversity, from the [[Ghegs]] in the North to the [[Tosks]] in the South, the two major ethnic subgroups. It is an integral part of the national identity, strongly influenced by the country's long and turbulent [[History of Albania|history]],<ref name=\"albmusic\"/> which forced [[Albanians]] to protect their culture from their overlords by living in rural and remote mountains.\n\nDiverse Albanian [[folk music]] includes [[Monophony|monophonic]] and [[Polyphony|polyphonic]] styles, [[antiphon|response]]s, choral, instrumental and vocal music. Each region has a unique musical tradition that reflects its history, [[Albanian language|language]] and [[Albanian culture|culture]].<ref name=\"albmusic\">{{cite web|author1=SPIRO J. SHETUNI|title=Albanian Traditional Music - An Introduction, with Sheet Music and Lyrics for 48 Songs|url=https://www.galabri.com/foto/vallekeng/pdf/musicshetuni.pdf|website=galabri.com|language=English|format=PDF|access-date=2017-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226021850/https://www.galabri.com/foto/vallekeng/pdf/musicshetuni.pdf|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> Polyphonic singing and song forms are primarily found in South Albania, while in the North they are predominantly monophonic. [[Albanian iso-polyphony]] has been declared an [[UNESCO]] [[UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists|Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=[[UNESCO]] [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]]|title=Albanian folk iso-polyphony|url=https://ich.unesco.org/en/RL/albanian-folk-iso-polyphony-00155|website=ich.unesco.org|language=English}}</ref> The [[Gjirokast\u00ebr National Folklore Festival]], held every five years in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]], is an important venue exhibiting traditional Albanian music.\n\nAlbanian music extends to ancient [[Illyria]] and [[Ancient Greece]], with influences from the [[Roman Empire|Roman]], [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] and [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/> It is evident in [[Architecture of Albania|archeological findings]] such as arenas, [[odeon (building)|odeon]]s, theatre buildings and amphitheatres, all over Albania. The remains of temples, libraries, sculptures and paintings of ancient dancers, singers and musical instruments, have been found in territories inhabited by the ancient Illyrians and ancient Greeks.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\n[[Church music|Church singing]] was performed throughout early [[Middle Ages]] in Albania by choirs or soloists in [[ecclesiastical]] centers such as [[Berat]], [[Durr\u00ebs]] and [[Shkod\u00ebr]].<ref name=\"historyofalbmusic\">{{cite web|author1=[[Charles University]]|title=Choral Music in Albania|url=https://is.cuni.cz/webapps/zzp/download/120164852|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226182252/https://is.cuni.cz/webapps/zzp/download/120164852|url-status=live|archive-date=2017-12-26|website=is.cuni.cz|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> The Middle Ages in Albania included [[choral music]] and [[traditional music]].<ref name=\"historyofalbmusic\"/> [[John Koukouzelis|Sh\u00ebn Jan Kukuzeli]], a singer, composer and musical innovator of Albanian origin, is one of the earliest known musicians.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Elsie|title=Meine B\u00fccher Mein Verlauf B\u00fccher bei Google Play Historical Dictionary of Albania|publisher=Scarecrow Press, 2010|isbn=9780810873803|page=252|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=haFlGXIg8uoC&pg=PA252&lpg=PA252&dq=Robert+Elsie+Jan+Kukuzeli&source=bl&ots=dOyO4OL9PU&sig=o3NQs32SX-dCXA5lXBUmKW3YGBg&hl=sq&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Robert%20Elsie%20Jan%20Kukuzeli&f=false}}</ref>\n\nInternationally renowned [[contemporary music]]ians of Albanian origin from Albania and [[Albanian diaspora]] include [[Action Bronson]], [[Elvana Gjata]], [[Ava Max]], [[Bebe Rexha]], [[Dua Lipa]], [[Era Istrefi]], Albert Stanaj, [[Dafina Zeqiri]], [[Eleni Foureira]], [[Gashi (rapper)|Gashi]], [[Ermal Meta]], [[Enca Haxhia|Enca]], [[Elhaida Dani]], [[Noizy]], [[Unikkatil]], and [[Rita Ora]]. In the field of [[classical music]], several Albanian sopranos and tenors have gained international recognition including Rame Lahaj, [[Inva Mula]], [[Marie Kraja]], [[Saimir Pirgu]] and [[Ermonela Jaho]], and the composer [[Vasil Tole]] a member of the Academy of Sciences of Albania\n\n== Folk music ==\n\n[[File:Albanian dialects.svg|200px|thumb|left|[[Albanian dialects|Dialects]] of the [[Albanian language]].]]\n\nAlbanian [[folk music]] has a deep history and can be separated into three major stylistic groups such as the northern [[Gheg]]s, southern [[Lab\u00ebria|Labs]] and [[Tosk]]s and with other important urban [[music area]]s around [[Shkod\u00ebr]] and [[Tirana]].<ref name=\"albmusic\"/> It reflects the cultural and political history of the [[Albanian people]] and geographic position in [[Southern Europe]] and [[Mediterranean Sea]].\n\nThe northern and southern traditions are contrasted by the rugged and heroic tone of the north and the relaxed, gentle and exceptionally beautiful form of the south. These disparate styles are unified by the intensity that both performers and listeners give to their music as a medium for patriotic expression and as a vehicle carrying the narrative of [[oral history]], as well as certain characteristics like the use of [[rhythm]]s such as 3/8, 5/8 and 10/8.<ref name=\"roughguide\">Burton, Kim. \"The Eagle Has Landed\". 2000. In Broughton, Simon and Ellingham, Mark with McConnachie, James and Duane, Orla (Ed.), ''World Music, Vol. 1: Africa, Europe and the Middle East'', pp 1-6. [[Rough Guides]] Ltd, Penguin Books. {{ISBN|1-85828-636-0}}. Burton notes that even ''lullabies contained the wish that the infant would grow up to be a strong worker for Enver and the Party.''</ref><ref>Arbatsky, Yuri, cited in Koco with the footnote ''Translated and published by Filip Fishta in Shkolla Komb\u00ebtare (The National School; No.1, May 1939), 19, and quoted from his Preface to [[Pjet\u00ebr Dungu]]'s Lyra Shqiptare (see note 2).''</ref>\n\nAlbanian folk songs can be divided into major groups, the heroic epics of the north and the sweetly melodic [[lullaby|lullabies]], [[love song]]s, [[wedding music]], [[work song]]s and other kinds of song. The music of various festivals and holidays is also an important part of Albanian folk song, especially those that celebrate [[Lazarus of Bethany|Lazarus Day]], which inaugurates the springtime. Lullabies and [[lament]]s are very important kinds of Albanian folk song, and are generally performed by solo women.<ref name=\"koco\">{{cite web|title=Albanian Music|work=Eno Koco at the [[University of Leeds]]|url=http://www.enokoco.com/musicology/publishing-in-english/|accessdate=28 August 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212073734/http://www.enokoco.com/musicology/publishing-in-english/|archivedate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Northern Albania ===\n\n[[File:Lahuta.jpg|thumb|160px|right|A [[lahuta]] player wearing [[traditional Albanian clothing]].]]\n\nThe [[Gheg Albanian|Ghegs]] from North of the [[Shkumbini River]] are known for a distinctive variety of sung [[epic poetry]]. The music of the north is particularly [[Monophony|monophonic]]. Many of these are about the struggles of the Albanian people and history, the constant Albanian themes of honour, hospitality, treachery and revenge but also [[Skanderbeg]], a legendary 15th century warrior who led the struggle against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]]s.<ref name=\"historyofalbmusic\"/> These traditions are a form of [[oral history]] for the Ghegs and also preserve and inculcate moral codes and social values, necessary in a society that, until the early 20th century, relied on blood feuds as its primary means of law enforcement.<ref>Burton, pg. 2 ''Both epic traditions serve as a medium for oral history in what was until quite recently, a pre-literate society... and also preserve and inculcate moral codes and social values. In a culture that retained the blood-feud as its primary means of law enforcement until well into this century such codes were literally matters of life and death. Song was one of the most efficient ways of making sure that each member of the tribe was aware of what obligations he or she was bound by.''</ref>\n\nThe most traditional variety of epic poetry is the [[Albanian Songs of the Frontier Warriors]]. These epic poems are sung, accompanied by a [[lahuta]]. It is rarely performed in modern Albania, but is found in the northern highlands within the [[Dukagjin highlands]] and [[Mal\u00ebsia]].<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> Other styles of epics also include the K\u00ebng\u00eb trimash or kreshnik\u00ebsh ({{lang-en|Songs of brave men or frontier warriors}}), [[ballad]]s and [[vajtim|maje krahi]]s ({{lang|en|cries}}). Major epics include ''Mujo and Halil'' and ''Halil and Hajrije''.<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n\nSomewhat further south, around [[Debar|Dib\u00ebr]] and [[K\u00ebr\u00e7ov\u00eb]] in [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]], the lahuta is not used, replaced by the [[\u00e7ifteli]], a two-stringed instrument in which one string is used for the [[Drone (music)|drone]] and one for the [[melody]]. Though men are the traditional performers (exception made for the [[Albanian sworn virgins|sworn virgins]]), women have increasingly been taking part in epic balladry.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nAlong with the def, [[\u00e7ifteli]] and sharki are used in a style of dance and pastoral songs. Homemade [[wind instrument]]s are traditionally used by [[shepherd]]s in northern Albania; these include the zumar\u00eb, an unusual kind of clarinet. This shepherds' music is \"melancholic and contemplative\" in tone.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> The songs called ''maje-krahi'' are another important part of North Albanian folk song; these were originally used by mountaineers to communicate over wide distances, but are now seen as songs. ''Maje-krahi'' songs require the full range of the voice and are full of \"melismatic nuances and falsetto cries\".<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Southern Albania === <!-- This section is linked from [[Pentatonic scale]] -->\n{{further|Albanian iso-polyphony}}\n\n[[File:Fustanela_001.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Folk group from Southern Albania]]\n\nSouthern Albanian music is soft and gentle, and polyphonic in nature with similarities with Greek music on [[polyphonic song of Epirus]]. [[Vlor\u00eb]] in the southwest has perhaps the most unusual vocal traditions in the area, with four distinct parts (''taker'', ''thrower'', ''turner'' and ''drone'') that combine to create a complex and emotionally cathartic melody. Author Kim Burton has described the melodies as \"decorated with [[falsetto]] and [[vibrato]], sometimes interrupted by wild and mournful cries\". This polyphonic vocal music is full of power that \"stems from the tension between the immense emotional weight it carries, rooted in centuries of pride, poverty and oppression, and the strictly formal, almost ritualistic nature of its structure\".<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nSouth Albania is also known for funeral laments with a chorus and one to two soloists with overlapping, mournful voices. There is a prominent folk love song tradition in the south, in which performers use free rhythm and consonant harmonies, elaborated with [[ornament (music)|ornamentation]] and [[melisma]].<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n\nThe [[Tosk Albanian|Tosk]] people are known for ensembles consisting of [[violin]]s, [[clarinet]]s, lahut\u00eb (a kind of [[lute]]) and [[Def (instrument)|def]]. [[Eli Fara]], a popular \u00e9migr\u00e9 performer, is from [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], but the city of [[P\u00ebrmet]] is the center for southern musical innovation, producing artists like Remzi Lela and Laver Bariu. Lela is of special note, having founded a musical dynasty that continues with his descendants playing a part in most of the major music institutions in Tirana.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nSouthern instrumental music includes the sedate kaba, an ensemble-driven by a clarinet or violin alongside accordions and llaut\u00ebs. The kaba is an improvised and melancholic style with melodies that Kim Burton describes as \"both fresh and ancient\", \"ornamented with swoops, glides and growls of an almost vocal quality\", exemplifying the \"combination of passion with restraint that is the hallmark of Albanian culture.\"<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nThe ethnic [[Greeks in Albania|Greek]] inhabitants of the country's southern parts, have a music very similar to the [[music of Epirus]] in Greece.\n\n=== Instrumentation ===\n\n[[File:Lahuta_QKVF.jpg|thumb|160px|A [[Lahuta|lahut\u00eb]] from [[Mirdit\u00eb District|Mirdit\u00eb]] in the north.]]\n\nInstrumentation are an integral part of Albanian folk music, especially in the north. Those instruments can be divided into [[String instrument|string]], [[Wind instrument|wind]] and [[Percussion instrument|percussion]] categories. They vary from region to region and are used frequently throughout the entire country, performing both dance and instrumental polyphonic folk music.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\nThe [[lahuta]], a single-[[stringed instrument]], is rooted in Albanian [[epic poetry]] with emphasis on important historical and patriotic events from [[History of Albania|history]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Bahtir Sheholli|title=Traditional and Contemporary Elements in Albanian Folk Music|url=https://aab-edu.net/assets/uploads/2016/10/11-Bahtir-Sheholli-anglisht.pdf|website=aab-edu.net|page=2|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Arbnora Dushi|title=On Collecting and Publishing the Albanian Oral Epic|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326297060_On_Collecting_and_Publishing_the_Albanian_Oral_Epic |website=webcache.googleusercontent.com|page=1|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> It is usually played only by men during winter evenings by the fireplace. The instrument is primarily widespread in the mountainous northern area of the country but can be also found in the center of the country.<ref name=\"albmusic\"/> It is often made from a single wood block composed of various types of woods including [[maple]], [[spruce]] and [[oak]]. The head of the lahuta is decorated with symbols of ancient cults such as the head of the capricorn, which is the symbol of the [[Helmet of Skanderbeg]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Johannes Scherzer, Johannes Varga|title=Die Lahut\u00eb|url=http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_lahute.htm|website=soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de|language=German|access-date=2017-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226130330/http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_lahute.htm|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u00c7iftelias.jpg|160px|thumb|left|[[\u00c7ifteli]] was used since the [[Ottoman Albania|Ottoman occupation of Albania]].]]\n\n[[\u00c7ifteli]]a is a long necked stringed instrument and frequently used by [[Gheg Albanian]]s in northeastern [[Albania]], [[Kosovo]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]].<ref name=\"hisalbmc\">{{cite web|author1=Marinela Mahony|title=An investigation of the polyphonic folk music of Albania|url=https://repository.up.ac.za/bitstream/handle/2263/27337/dissertation.pdf?sequence=1|website=repository.up.ac.za|page=28|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> It is an integral part of northern traditional instrumental ensembles, commonly played in the context of northern wedding music.\n\n[[Double clarinet|Fyell]], also known as Zumare, is a similar instrument to a [[pennywhistle]] and is mostly played by shepherds in the north along with a shepherd's flute.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fyell|url=http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_fyell.htm|website=soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de|language=German|access-date=2017-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226234735/http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_fyell.htm|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> The instrument contains five holes in each pipe and a bell. The melodies which are played with a fyell are [[Homophony|homophonic]] and sounds nasal as well as very strong and powerful.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\n[[Violin]]a is usually used since the 19th century in both the northern and southern region. In the past, it was held in a vertical position like a [[violoncello]] or a lahuta but is not practiced anymore.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\n* [[Clarinet]] \n* [[Goblet drum|Qypi]]\n* [[Zurna|Surlja]] \n* [[Dayereh|Dajreja]]\n* [[Gaida|Gajda]]\n* [[Davul|Lodra]] \n* [[Tambourine|Defi]]\n* [[Toubeleki]]\n*[[Albanian bagpipe|Albanian Bagpipe]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Popular music==\n\n[[File:Parashqevi_Simaku.gif|thumb|200px|[[Parashqevi Simaku]] was a popular singer of the 1980s]]\n\nThe city of [[Shkod\u00ebr]] has long been one of the most important cultural centers of Albania, and its early 20th century music is considered as one of the most sophisticated in the country.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> Traditional musicians from Shkod\u00ebr include [[Bujar Qamili]], Lu\u00e7ie Miloti, Xhevdet Hafizi and Bik Ndoja.\n\nAlbania's capital, Tirana, is the home of popular music dominated by [[Romani people|Romani]] influences and has been popularized at home and in emigrant communities internationally by Merita Halili, [[Parashqevi Simaku]], and Myslim Lela.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nOther voices in contemporary Albanian music include [[Va\u00e7e Zela]] and [[Pavlina Nikaj]] of Tirana, and [[Nexhmije Pagarusha]] of Prishtina.\n\n[[File:Band of Freedom 1909.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The Band of Freedom, a musical group of the [[Albanian National Awakening|National Renaissance]] that was active in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], 1909.]]\n\n===1930s Urban Song===\nThe [[Albanian Urban Lyric Song]] is a tradition that started in Albania in the 18th century but culminated in the 1930s.<ref name=\"Ko\u00e7o2004\">{{harvnb|Ko\u00e7o|2004|p=ix}}</ref> These songs are a major part of Albania's music heritage, but have been little-studied by [[ethnomusicology|ethnomusicologists]], who prefer to focus on the rural folk music that they see as being more authentically Albanian.\nOut of this [[melting pot]] of local and imported styles came a kind of lyrical art song based in the cities of [[Shkodra]], [[Elbasan]], [[Berat]] and [[Kor\u00e7a]]. Though similar traditions existed in other places, they were little recorded and remain largely unknown. \n[[File:Tefta Tashko Ko\u00e7o.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Portrait of [[Tefta Tashko-Ko\u00e7o|Tefta Tashko]]]]\nBy the end of the 19th century, Albanian [[nationalism]] was inspiring many to attempt to remove the elements of Turkish music from Albanian culture, a desire that was intensified following independence in 1912; bands that formed during this era like the Kor\u00e7\u00eb-based Lira Chorus<ref>http://www.irex.org/sites/default/files/Tochka.pdf{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> played a variety of European styles, including [[march (music)|march]]es and [[waltz]]es. Urban song in the early 20th century could be divided into two styles: the historic or nationalistic style, and the lyrical style.<ref name=\"koco\"/> The lyrical style included a wide array of lullabies and other forms, as well as love songs.\n\n[[File:RoselaGjylbeguKM2009.jpg|right|200px|thumb|[[Rosela Gjylbegu]] performing the winning song at ''\u201cK\u00ebnga Magjike\u201d'' 2009]]\n\nIn the early decade of the 1930s, urban art song had been incorporated into classical music, while the singer [[Marie Kraja]] made a popular career out of art songs; she was one of Albania's first popular singers. The first recordings, however, of urban art song came as early as 1937, with the orchestral sounds of [[Tefta Tashko-Ko\u00e7o]].<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n\n===1950s and beyond===\nModern Albanian popular music uses instruments like the [[\u00e7ifteli]] and [[sharki]], which have been used in large bands since the [[Second World War]] to great popular acclaim; the same songs, accompanied by [[clarinet]] and [[accordion]], are performed at small weddings and celebrations.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\n[[Tallava]] is a music genre originating in [[Kosovo]], also popular in [[Albania]] and the [[Republic of Macedonia]], in the Albanian-speaking communities.<ref name=\"balkansmusic\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yJ60SHL4R-0C&pg=PA78 |title=Music in the Balkans |publisher=BRILL |last=Samson |first=Jim |year=2013 |isbn=978-90-04-25037-6 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.telegrafi.com/lajme/refleksion-sociologjik-mbi-kicin-e-muzikes-tallava-26-1293.html |title=Refleksion sociologjik mbi ki\u00e7in e muzik\u00ebs tallava |access-date=2015-09-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114204/http://www.telegrafi.com/lajme/refleksion-sociologjik-mbi-kicin-e-muzikes-tallava-26-1293.html |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"kosovo\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uSaH1bKAb8QC&pg=PA41 | title=Kosovo | publisher=BRADT | author=Gail Warrander and Verena Knaus | year=2010}}</ref> Having originated in the Roma community in Kosovo in the 1990s, it is oriental-sounding, and perceived of as low-status.{{sfn|Samson|2013|p=78}} Nevertheless, it is becoming increasingly popular in Albania and Macedonia.{{sfn|Samson|2013|p=79}} It is identified as part of the wider [[Pop-folk]] genre of the [[Southeastern Europe]], which includes [[Chalga]] from Bulgaria, [[Skiladiko]] from Greece, [[Manele]] from Romania and [[Turbo-folk]] from Serbia.<ref name=\"Bayer2009\">{{cite book|author=Natalie Bayer|title=Crossing Munich|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fV5LAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Silke Schreiber|isbn=978-3-88960-108-7|quote=Formen wie: tallava in Albanien, chalga in Bulgarien, skil\u00e1diko in ... in Rum\u00e4nien, turbo folk in Serbien usw}}</ref>\n\n===Albanian music in Macedonia and Kosovo===\n{{main|Music of the Republic of Macedonia|Music of Kosovo}}\n\n[[Kosovo]] has been home to many important Albanian musicians and the same can be said for Macedonia. Prior to the [[Kosovo War]], there was a thriving music industry in Kosovo, which reached new heights in recent years. The Kosovar music industry was home to many famous musicians, including the famous [[Nexhmije Pagarusha]], Ismet Peja and the romantic, more elaborate [[Qamili i Vog\u00ebl]] of [[Gjakov\u00eb|Gjakova]].<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> The Macedonian band V\u00ebllez\u00ebrit Aliu became well- known for the traditional vocal duets accompanied by drum box, electric bass, synthesizer and clarinet or saxophone.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> ''[[Gjurm\u00ebt]]'' is one of the most famous and influential 1980s [[Albanian rock|rock]] bands from [[Pristina]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.albhitee.net/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-07-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629231409/http://albhitee.net/ |archive-date=2016-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Rock ===\n{{main|Rock music in Albania}}\n\n[[Rock music|Rock]] arrived in Albania, particularly in [[Kosovo]], in 1950 with an American and British influence. The first distinctively Albanian rock band was Blue Star founded in [[Pristina]]. \n{{Clear}}\n\n== Classical music ==\n\n=== Opera ===\n\n[[File:Fan Stilian Noli.jpg|thumb|right|[[Fan S. Noli]] <br /> {{small|1882\u20141965}}]]\n\n[[Palok\u00eb Kurti]] is usually said to be among the founders of Albanian opera.<ref name=\"cmoa\">{{cite web|title=Classical Music in Albania|url=http://frosina.org/classical-music-in-albania/|website=frosina.org|language=English}}</ref> Composer and priest, Martin Gjoka is also considered to be one of the most important founders of Albanian classical music.<ref name=\"cmoa\"/> Gjoka is said to be the first Albanian musician who showed great interest in traditional Albanian folk music considerably that of the deep [[Geography of Albania#Topography and hydrography|mountainous areas]] of the [[Northern Mountain Range (Albania)|north]] of Albania that was less influenced by foreign music.<ref name=\"cmoa\"/><ref name=\"frosina\">{{cite web|work=Frosina Information Network|title=The Tradition of Classical Music In Albania|url=http://www.frosina.org/about/infobits.asp?id=136|accessdate=28 August 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051017030453/http://www.frosina.org/about/infobits.asp?id=136|archivedate=17 October 2005}}</ref> During his lifetime, he composed several vocal and instrumental music using elements of urban art song and the folk melodies of the north.\n\nIn the 19th and 20th century, [[Fan S. Noli]] and [[Mikel Koliqi]] contributed to the development of classical music culture in Albania. They achieved prominence, with Noli using urban folk songs in his ''[[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] Overture'' and is also known for a symphonic poem called ''[[Gjergj Kastriot Scanderbeg|Scanderberg]]''.<ref name=\"koco\"/> Koliqi spent much of his life in prison for his religious beliefs, but managed to compose [[melodrama]]s such as ''[[Siege of Shkodra (1474)|The Siege of Shkod\u00ebr]]'', ''The Red Scarf'' and ''[[Rozafa Castle|Rozafa]]''.\n\nOther pivotal composers in modern Albanian classical music were Thoma Nassi, [[Kristo Kono]], Frano Ndoja and Lec Kurti who composed \"Arbereshja\" in 1915. \n[[Prenk Jakova]] became well known for operas including ''Scanderbeg'' and ''Mrika'', which were influenced by traditional [[Italian opera]], the [[belcanto]] style and Albanian folk music. [[\u00c7esk Zadeja]] composed in many styles, from symphonies to ballets, beginning in 1956, and also helped found the Music Conservatory of Tirana, the Theatre of Opera and Ballet, and the Assembly of Songs and Dances.<ref name=\"frosina\"/>\n\nLater in the middle of the 20th century, Albanian composers came to focus on [[ballet]]s, opera and other styles; these included [[Tonin Harapi]], [[Tish Daija]], [[Nikolla Zoraqi]], Thoma Gaqi, [[Feim Ibrahimi]], Shp\u00ebtim Kushta and many others. Since the [[Fall of communism in Albania|fall of the communism]] in Albania in the 21st century, composers like [[Aleksand\u00ebr Pe\u00e7i]], ethnologist musician [[Ramadan Sokoli]], Sokol Shup, Endri Sina, P\u00ebllumb Vorpsi and [[Vasil Tole]] have arisen, as have new music institutions like the Society of Music Professionals and the Society of New Albanian Music.<ref name=\"frosina\"/>\n\nThe contemporary opera artists such as [[Inva Mula]], [[Ermonela Jaho]] and [[Saimir Pirgu]] have achieved international recognition for their music.\n\n==Contemporary music==\n[[File:Ardit Gjebrea KM2009.jpg|thumb|left|190px|Noted singer and entertainer [[Ardit Gjebrea]] founded the [[K\u00ebnga Magjike]] festival in 1999.]]\n{{Main|Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs|K\u00ebnga Magjike}}\n{{See also|Albanian rock|Albanian hip hop}}\nIn Albania, the most prominent rock bands and individuals only appeared after 1990 as rock music was prohibited. However, youth groups found ways to listen it through clandestine channels.<ref>Miranda Vickers, James Pettifer: [https://books.google.com/books?id=mnTCPH_ZGW4C&pg=PA299&dq=albanian+rock#v=onepage&q=albanian%20rock&f=false Albania: from anarchy to a Balkan identity], page 121 \"...in the 1970s Beatles songs could only be heard in clandestine condition...\"</ref>\n\nFurthermore, electronic music has become a mainstream music genre in Albania. Albanian artists and renowned DJs such as DJ Aldo, Vin Veli, DJ Sardi, Dj Tedd and others are successfully collaborating mainly with Italian and Romanian artists, while showcasing themselves in renown clubs in Tirana and in annual music festivals along the [[Albanian Riviera]] such as Turtle Fest and Soundwave Albania.\n{{Clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Music of Albania}}\n* [[:Category:Albanian singers|Albanian singers]]\n* [[Albanians]]\n* [[Culture of Albania]]\n* [[Music of Kosovo]] \n* [[List of Albanian musicians]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{citation|author=Arbatsky, Yuri|year=1953|title=Beating the Tupan in the Central Balkans |publisher=The Newbery Library}}\n*{{citation|last=Ko\u00e7o|first=Eno|title=Albanian urban lyric song in the 1930s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oWL2ZKPimKEC&pg=PA252|year=2004|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-4890-0}}\n*{{citation|last=Sugarman|first= Jane C.|year=1997|title=Engendering Song: Singing and Subjectivity at Prespa Albanian Weddings|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=0-226-77973-4}}\n* [http://upetd.up.ac.za/thesis/available/etd-08172011-150502/unrestricted/dissertation.pdf Mahony, Marinela. \"An Investigation of the Polyphonic Folk Music of Albania\". Dissertation. University of Pretoria, Pretoria: 2011.]\n* Rice, Timothy; Porter, James and Chris Goertzen. \"Albanian Music [by] Jane Sugarman.\" ''The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music Online'' 8, 2000: 986-1004.\n* Taylor, Roger. Review of \"The Music of Albania\". ''Brio'' 32, 1995: 40-42\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120405223217/http://www.newsound.org.rs/clanci_eng/7.%20Milto%20Vako.pdf Vako, Milto. \"The Origin and Development of Albanian Choral Music.\" ''New Sound: International Magazine for Music'' 28 2006.]\n*''Kenge, Albanian Piano Music'', Vol. 1, Kirsten Johnson, piano, Guild GMCD 7257.\n*''Rapsodi, Albanian Piano Music'', Vol. 2, Kirsten Johnson, piano, Guild GMCD 7300.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ville-ge.ch/meg/public_ph.php?id=HR1085-1/1 Audio clip: traditional Albanian music.]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Mus\u00e9e d'ethnographie de Gen\u00e8ve]]. Accessed November 25, 2010.\n* [http://www.isopolifonia.com Isopolyphony Official Website]\n* [http://www.radioemigranti.com Radio Emigranti \u2013 Albanian Traditional Music Radio Station]\n* [http://www.predavatel.com/mk/play/mrt_radio3_live Radio Skopje 3 Live Streaming - Skopje, Macedonia]\n* [http://tunein.com/tuner/?StationId=8031& Radio Tirana International Service LIVE]{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Music of Europe}}\n{{Music of Southeastern Europe (the Balkans)}}\n{{Albania topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Music Of Albania}}\n[[Category:Albanian music| ]]\n[[Category:Southern European music]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Music coming from the country of Albania}}\n{{Culture of Albania}}{{Music of Albania}}\n\nThe '''Music of Albania''' ({{lang-sq|Muzika Shqiptare}}) is associated with the country of [[Albania]] and [[Albanian diaspora|Albanian communities]]. [[Music]] has a long tradition in the country and is known for its regional diversity, from the [[Ghegs]] in the North to the [[Tosks]] in the South, the two major ethnic subgroups. It is an integral part of the national identity, strongly influenced by the country's long and turbulent [[History of Albania|history]],<ref name=\"albmusic\"/> which forced [[Albanians]] to protect their culture from their overlords by living in rural and remote mountains.\n\nDiverse Albanian [[folk music]] includes [[Monophony|monophonic]] and [[Polyphony|polyphonic]] styles, [[antiphon|response]]s, choral, instrumental and vocal music. Each region has a unique musical tradition that reflects its history, [[Albanian language|language]] and [[Albanian culture|culture]].<ref name=\"albmusic\">{{cite web|author1=SPIRO J. SHETUNI|title=Albanian Traditional Music - An Introduction, with Sheet Music and Lyrics for 48 Songs|url=https://www.galabri.com/foto/vallekeng/pdf/musicshetuni.pdf|website=galabri.com|language=English|format=PDF|access-date=2017-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226021850/https://www.galabri.com/foto/vallekeng/pdf/musicshetuni.pdf|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> Polyphonic singing and song forms are primarily found in South Albania, while in the North they are predominantly monophonic. [[Albanian iso-polyphony]] has been declared an [[UNESCO]] [[UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists|Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=[[UNESCO]] [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]]|title=Albanian folk iso-polyphony|url=https://ich.unesco.org/en/RL/albanian-folk-iso-polyphony-00155|website=ich.unesco.org|language=English}}</ref> The [[Gjirokast\u00ebr National Folklore Festival]], held every five years in [[Gjirokast\u00ebr]], is an important venue exhibiting traditional Albanian music.\n\nAlbanian music extends to ancient [[Illyria]] and [[Ancient Greece]], with influences from the [[Roman Empire|Roman]], [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] and [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/> It is evident in [[Architecture of Albania|archeological findings]] such as arenas, [[odeon (building)|odeon]]s, theatre buildings and amphitheatres, all over Albania. The remains of temples, libraries, sculptures and paintings of ancient dancers, singers and musical instruments, have been found in territories inhabited by the ancient Illyrians and ancient Greeks.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\n[[Church music|Church singing]] was performed throughout early [[Middle Ages]] in Albania by choirs or soloists in [[ecclesiastical]] centers such as [[Berat]], [[Durr\u00ebs]] and [[Shkod\u00ebr]].<ref name=\"historyofalbmusic\">{{cite web|author1=[[Charles University]]|title=Choral Music in Albania|url=https://is.cuni.cz/webapps/zzp/download/120164852|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226182252/https://is.cuni.cz/webapps/zzp/download/120164852|url-status=live|archive-date=2017-12-26|website=is.cuni.cz|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> The Middle Ages in Albania included [[choral music]] and [[traditional music]].<ref name=\"historyofalbmusic\"/> [[John Koukouzelis|Sh\u00ebn Jan Kukuzeli]], a singer, composer and musical innovator of Albanian origin, is one of the earliest known musicians.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Elsie|title=Meine B\u00fccher Mein Verlauf B\u00fccher bei Google Play Historical Dictionary of Albania|publisher=Scarecrow Press, 2010|isbn=9780810873803|page=252|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=haFlGXIg8uoC&pg=PA252&lpg=PA252&dq=Robert+Elsie+Jan+Kukuzeli&source=bl&ots=dOyO4OL9PU&sig=o3NQs32SX-dCXA5lXBUmKW3YGBg&hl=sq&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Robert%20Elsie%20Jan%20Kukuzeli&f=false}}</ref>\n\nInternationally renowned [[contemporary music]]ians of Albanian origin from Albania and [[Albanian diaspora]] include [[Action Bronson]], [[Elvana Gjata]], [[Ava Max]], [[Bebe Rexha]], [[Dua Lipa]], [[Era Istrefi]], Albert Stanaj, [[Dafina Zeqiri]], [[Eleni Foureira]], [[Gashi (rapper)|Gashi]], [[Ermal Meta]], [[Enca Haxhia|Enca]], [[Elhaida Dani]], [[Noizy]], [[Unikkatil]], and [[Rita Ora]]. In the field of [[classical music]], several Albanian sopranos and tenors have gained international recognition including Rame Lahaj, [[Inva Mula]], [[Marie Kraja]], [[Saimir Pirgu]] and [[Ermonela Jaho]], and the composer [[Vasil Tole]] a member of the Academy of Sciences of Albania\n\n== Folk music ==\n\n[[File:Albanian dialects.svg|200px|thumb|left|[[Albanian dialects|Dialects]] of the [[Albanian language]].]]\n\nAlbanian [[folk music]] has a deep history and can be separated into three major stylistic groups such as the northern [[Gheg]]s, southern [[Lab\u00ebria|Labs]] and [[Tosk]]s and with other important urban [[music area]]s around [[Shkod\u00ebr]] and [[Tirana]].<ref name=\"albmusic\"/> It reflects the cultural and political history of the [[Albanian people]] and geographic position in [[Southern Europe]] and [[Mediterranean Sea]].\n\nThe northern and southern traditions are contrasted by the rugged and heroic tone of the north and the relaxed, gentle and exceptionally beautiful form of the south. These disparate styles are unified by the intensity that both performers and listeners give to their music as a medium for patriotic expression and as a vehicle carrying the narrative of [[oral history]], as well as certain characteristics like the use of [[rhythm]]s such as 3/8, 5/8 and 10/8.<ref name=\"roughguide\">Burton, Kim. \"The Eagle Has Landed\". 2000. In Broughton, Simon and Ellingham, Mark with McConnachie, James and Duane, Orla (Ed.), ''World Music, Vol. 1: Africa, Europe and the Middle East'', pp 1-6. [[Rough Guides]] Ltd, Penguin Books. {{ISBN|1-85828-636-0}}. Burton notes that even ''lullabies contained the wish that the infant would grow up to be a strong worker for Enver and the Party.''</ref><ref>Arbatsky, Yuri, cited in Koco with the footnote ''Translated and published by Filip Fishta in Shkolla Komb\u00ebtare (The National School; No.1, May 1939), 19, and quoted from his Preface to [[Pjet\u00ebr Dungu]]'s Lyra Shqiptare (see note 2).''</ref>\n\nAlbanian folk songs can be divided into major groups, the heroic epics of the north and the sweetly melodic [[lullaby|lullabies]], [[love song]]s, [[wedding music]], [[work song]]s and other kinds of song. The music of various festivals and holidays is also an important part of Albanian folk song, especially those that celebrate [[Lazarus of Bethany|Lazarus Day]], which inaugurates the springtime. Lullabies and [[lament]]s are very important kinds of Albanian folk song, and are generally performed by solo women.<ref name=\"koco\">{{cite web|title=Albanian Music|work=Eno Koco at the [[University of Leeds]]|url=http://www.enokoco.com/musicology/publishing-in-english/|accessdate=28 August 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212073734/http://www.enokoco.com/musicology/publishing-in-english/|archivedate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Northern Albania ===\n\n[[File:Lahuta.jpg|thumb|160px|right|A [[lahuta]] player wearing [[traditional Albanian clothing]].]]\n\nThe [[Gheg Albanian|Ghegs]] from North of the [[Shkumbini River]] are known for a distinctive variety of sung [[epic poetry]]. The music of the north is particularly [[Monophony|monophonic]]. Many of these are about the struggles of the Albanian people and history, the constant Albanian themes of honour, hospitality, treachery and revenge but also [[Skanderbeg]], a legendary 15th century warrior who led the struggle against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]]s.<ref name=\"historyofalbmusic\"/> These traditions are a form of [[oral history]] for the Ghegs and also preserve and inculcate moral codes and social values, necessary in a society that, until the early 20th century, relied on blood feuds as its primary means of law enforcement.<ref>Burton, pg. 2 ''Both epic traditions serve as a medium for oral history in what was until quite recently, a pre-literate society... and also preserve and inculcate moral codes and social values. In a culture that retained the blood-feud as its primary means of law enforcement until well into this century such codes were literally matters of life and death. Song was one of the most efficient ways of making sure that each member of the tribe was aware of what obligations he or she was bound by.''</ref>\n\nThe most traditional variety of epic poetry is the [[Albanian Songs of the Frontier Warriors]]. These epic poems are sung, accompanied by a [[lahuta]]. It is rarely performed in modern Albania, but is found in the northern highlands within the [[Dukagjin highlands]] and [[Mal\u00ebsia]].<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> Other styles of epics also include the K\u00ebng\u00eb trimash or kreshnik\u00ebsh ({{lang-en|Songs of brave men or frontier warriors}}), [[ballad]]s and [[vajtim|maje krahi]]s ({{lang|en|cries}}). Major epics include ''Mujo and Halil'' and ''Halil and Hajrije''.<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n\nSomewhat further south, around [[Debar|Dib\u00ebr]] and [[K\u00ebr\u00e7ov\u00eb]] in [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]], the lahuta is not used, replaced by the [[\u00e7ifteli]], a two-stringed instrument in which one string is used for the [[Drone (music)|drone]] and one for the [[melody]]. Though men are the traditional performers (exception made for the [[Albanian sworn virgins|sworn virgins]]), women have increasingly been taking part in epic balladry.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nAlong with the def, [[\u00e7ifteli]] and sharki are used in a style of dance and pastoral songs. Homemade [[wind instrument]]s are traditionally used by [[shepherd]]s in northern Albania; these include the zumar\u00eb, an unusual kind of clarinet. This shepherds' music is \"melancholic and contemplative\" in tone.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> The songs called ''maje-krahi'' are another important part of North Albanian folk song; these were originally used by mountaineers to communicate over wide distances, but are now seen as songs. ''Maje-krahi'' songs require the full range of the voice and are full of \"melismatic nuances and falsetto cries\".<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Southern Albania === <!-- This section is linked from [[Pentatonic scale]] -->\n{{further|Albanian iso-polyphony}}\n\n[[File:Fustanela_001.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Folk group from Southern Albania]]\n\nSouthern Albanian music is soft and gentle, and polyphonic in nature with similarities with Greek music on [[polyphonic song of Epirus]]. [[Vlor\u00eb]] in the southwest has perhaps the most unusual vocal traditions in the area, with four distinct parts (''taker'', ''thrower'', ''turner'' and ''drone'') that combine to create a complex and emotionally cathartic melody. Author Kim Burton has described the melodies as \"decorated with [[falsetto]] and [[vibrato]], sometimes interrupted by wild and mournful cries\". This polyphonic vocal music is full of power that \"stems from the tension between the immense emotional weight it carries, rooted in centuries of pride, poverty and oppression, and the strictly formal, almost ritualistic nature of its structure\".<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nSouth Albania is also known for funeral laments with a chorus and one to two soloists with overlapping, mournful voices. There is a prominent folk love song tradition in the south, in which performers use free rhythm and consonant harmonies, elaborated with [[ornament (music)|ornamentation]] and [[melisma]].<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n\nThe [[Tosk Albanian|Tosk]] people are known for ensembles consisting of [[violin]]s, [[clarinet]]s, lahut\u00eb (a kind of [[lute]]) and [[Def (instrument)|def]]. [[Eli Fara]], a popular \u00e9migr\u00e9 performer, is from [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], but the city of [[P\u00ebrmet]] is the center for southern musical innovation, producing artists like Remzi Lela and Laver Bariu. Lela is of special note, having founded a musical dynasty that continues with his descendants playing a part in most of the major music institutions in Tirana.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nSouthern instrumental music includes the sedate kaba, an ensemble-driven by a clarinet or violin alongside accordions and llaut\u00ebs. The kaba is an improvised and melancholic style with melodies that Kim Burton describes as \"both fresh and ancient\", \"ornamented with swoops, glides and growls of an almost vocal quality\", exemplifying the \"combination of passion with restraint that is the hallmark of Albanian culture.\"<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nThe ethnic [[Greeks in Albania|Greek]] inhabitants of the country's southern parts, have a music very similar to the [[music of Epirus]] in Greece.\n\n=== Instrumentation ===\n\n[[File:Lahuta_QKVF.jpg|thumb|160px|A [[Lahuta|lahut\u00eb]] from [[Mirdit\u00eb District|Mirdit\u00eb]] in the north.]]\n\nInstrumentation are an integral part of Albanian folk music, especially in the north. Those instruments can be divided into [[String instrument|string]], [[Wind instrument|wind]] and [[Percussion instrument|percussion]] categories. They vary from region to region and are used frequently throughout the entire country, performing both dance and instrumental polyphonic folk music.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\nThe [[lahuta]], a single-[[stringed instrument]], is rooted in Albanian [[epic poetry]] with emphasis on important historical and patriotic events from [[History of Albania|history]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Bahtir Sheholli|title=Traditional and Contemporary Elements in Albanian Folk Music|url=https://aab-edu.net/assets/uploads/2016/10/11-Bahtir-Sheholli-anglisht.pdf|website=aab-edu.net|page=2|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Arbnora Dushi|title=On Collecting and Publishing the Albanian Oral Epic|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326297060_On_Collecting_and_Publishing_the_Albanian_Oral_Epic |website=webcache.googleusercontent.com|page=1|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> It is usually played only by men during winter evenings by the fireplace. The instrument is primarily widespread in the mountainous northern area of the country but can be also found in the center of the country.<ref name=\"albmusic\"/> It is often made from a single wood block composed of various types of woods including [[maple]], [[spruce]] and [[oak]]. The head of the lahuta is decorated with symbols of ancient cults such as the head of the capricorn, which is the symbol of the [[Helmet of Skanderbeg]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Johannes Scherzer, Johannes Varga|title=Die Lahut\u00eb|url=http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_lahute.htm|website=soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de|language=German|access-date=2017-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226130330/http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_lahute.htm|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u00c7iftelias.jpg|160px|thumb|left|[[\u00c7ifteli]] was used since the [[Ottoman Albania|Ottoman occupation of Albania]].]]\n\n[[\u00c7ifteli]]a is a long necked stringed instrument and frequently used by [[Gheg Albanian]]s in northeastern [[Albania]], [[Kosovo]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]].<ref name=\"hisalbmc\">{{cite web|author1=Marinela Mahony|title=An investigation of the polyphonic folk music of Albania|url=https://repository.up.ac.za/bitstream/handle/2263/27337/dissertation.pdf?sequence=1|website=repository.up.ac.za|page=28|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> It is an integral part of northern traditional instrumental ensembles, commonly played in the context of northern wedding music.\n\n[[Double clarinet|Fyell]], also known as Zumare, is a similar instrument to a [[pennywhistle]] and is mostly played by shepherds in the north along with a shepherd's flute.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fyell|url=http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_fyell.htm|website=soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de|language=German|access-date=2017-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226234735/http://soundscapeshqiperia.taucher-sound.de/instr_fyell.htm|archive-date=2017-12-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> The instrument contains five holes in each pipe and a bell. The melodies which are played with a fyell are [[Homophony|homophonic]] and sounds nasal as well as very strong and powerful.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\n[[Violin]]a is usually used since the 19th century in both the northern and southern region. In the past, it was held in a vertical position like a [[violoncello]] or a lahuta but is not practiced anymore.<ref name=\"hisalbmc\"/>\n\n* [[Clarinet]] \n* [[Goblet drum|Qypi]]\n* [[Zurna|Surlja]] \n* [[Dayereh|Dajreja]]\n* [[Gaida|Gajda]]\n* [[Davul|Lodra]] \n* [[Tambourine|Defi]]\n* [[Toubeleki]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Popular music==\n\n[[File:Parashqevi_Simaku.gif|thumb|200px|[[Parashqevi Simaku]] was a popular singer of the 1980s]]\n\nThe city of [[Shkod\u00ebr]] has long been one of the most important cultural centers of Albania, and its early 20th century music is considered as one of the most sophisticated in the country.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> Traditional musicians from Shkod\u00ebr include [[Bujar Qamili]], Lu\u00e7ie Miloti, Xhevdet Hafizi and Bik Ndoja.\n\nAlbania's capital, Tirana, is the home of popular music dominated by [[Romani people|Romani]] influences and has been popularized at home and in emigrant communities internationally by Merita Halili, [[Parashqevi Simaku]], and Myslim Lela.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\nOther voices in contemporary Albanian music include [[Va\u00e7e Zela]] and [[Pavlina Nikaj]] of Tirana, and [[Nexhmije Pagarusha]] of Prishtina.\n\n[[File:Band of Freedom 1909.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The Band of Freedom, a musical group of the [[Albanian National Awakening|National Renaissance]] that was active in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], 1909.]]\n\n===1930s Urban Song===\nThe [[Albanian Urban Lyric Song]] is a tradition that started in Albania in the 18th century but culminated in the 1930s.<ref name=\"Ko\u00e7o2004\">{{harvnb|Ko\u00e7o|2004|p=ix}}</ref> These songs are a major part of Albania's music heritage, but have been little-studied by [[ethnomusicology|ethnomusicologists]], who prefer to focus on the rural folk music that they see as being more authentically Albanian.\nOut of this [[melting pot]] of local and imported styles came a kind of lyrical art song based in the cities of [[Shkodra]], [[Elbasan]], [[Berat]] and [[Kor\u00e7a]]. Though similar traditions existed in other places, they were little recorded and remain largely unknown. \n[[File:Tefta Tashko Ko\u00e7o.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Portrait of [[Tefta Tashko-Ko\u00e7o|Tefta Tashko]]]]\nBy the end of the 19th century, Albanian [[nationalism]] was inspiring many to attempt to remove the elements of Turkish music from Albanian culture, a desire that was intensified following independence in 1912; bands that formed during this era like the Kor\u00e7\u00eb-based Lira Chorus<ref>http://www.irex.org/sites/default/files/Tochka.pdf{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> played a variety of European styles, including [[march (music)|march]]es and [[waltz]]es. Urban song in the early 20th century could be divided into two styles: the historic or nationalistic style, and the lyrical style.<ref name=\"koco\"/> The lyrical style included a wide array of lullabies and other forms, as well as love songs.\n\n[[File:RoselaGjylbeguKM2009.jpg|right|200px|thumb|[[Rosela Gjylbegu]] performing the winning song at ''\u201cK\u00ebnga Magjike\u201d'' 2009]]\n\nIn the early decade of the 1930s, urban art song had been incorporated into classical music, while the singer [[Marie Kraja]] made a popular career out of art songs; she was one of Albania's first popular singers. The first recordings, however, of urban art song came as early as 1937, with the orchestral sounds of [[Tefta Tashko-Ko\u00e7o]].<ref name=\"koco\"/>\n\n===1950s and beyond===\nModern Albanian popular music uses instruments like the [[\u00e7ifteli]] and [[sharki]], which have been used in large bands since the [[Second World War]] to great popular acclaim; the same songs, accompanied by [[clarinet]] and [[accordion]], are performed at small weddings and celebrations.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/>\n\n[[Tallava]] is a music genre originating in [[Kosovo]], also popular in [[Albania]] and the [[Republic of Macedonia]], in the Albanian-speaking communities.<ref name=\"balkansmusic\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yJ60SHL4R-0C&pg=PA78 |title=Music in the Balkans |publisher=BRILL |last=Samson |first=Jim |year=2013 |isbn=978-90-04-25037-6 |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.telegrafi.com/lajme/refleksion-sociologjik-mbi-kicin-e-muzikes-tallava-26-1293.html |title=Refleksion sociologjik mbi ki\u00e7in e muzik\u00ebs tallava |access-date=2015-09-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114204/http://www.telegrafi.com/lajme/refleksion-sociologjik-mbi-kicin-e-muzikes-tallava-26-1293.html |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"kosovo\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uSaH1bKAb8QC&pg=PA41 | title=Kosovo | publisher=BRADT | author=Gail Warrander and Verena Knaus | year=2010}}</ref> Having originated in the Roma community in Kosovo in the 1990s, it is oriental-sounding, and perceived of as low-status.{{sfn|Samson|2013|p=78}} Nevertheless, it is becoming increasingly popular in Albania and Macedonia.{{sfn|Samson|2013|p=79}} It is identified as part of the wider [[Pop-folk]] genre of the [[Southeastern Europe]], which includes [[Chalga]] from Bulgaria, [[Skiladiko]] from Greece, [[Manele]] from Romania and [[Turbo-folk]] from Serbia.<ref name=\"Bayer2009\">{{cite book|author=Natalie Bayer|title=Crossing Munich|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fV5LAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Silke Schreiber|isbn=978-3-88960-108-7|quote=Formen wie: tallava in Albanien, chalga in Bulgarien, skil\u00e1diko in ... in Rum\u00e4nien, turbo folk in Serbien usw}}</ref>\n\n===Albanian music in Macedonia and Kosovo===\n{{main|Music of the Republic of Macedonia|Music of Kosovo}}\n\n[[Kosovo]] has been home to many important Albanian musicians and the same can be said for Macedonia. Prior to the [[Kosovo War]], there was a thriving music industry in Kosovo, which reached new heights in recent years. The Kosovar music industry was home to many famous musicians, including the famous [[Nexhmije Pagarusha]], Ismet Peja and the romantic, more elaborate [[Qamili i Vog\u00ebl]] of [[Gjakov\u00eb|Gjakova]].<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> The Macedonian band V\u00ebllez\u00ebrit Aliu became well- known for the traditional vocal duets accompanied by drum box, electric bass, synthesizer and clarinet or saxophone.<ref name=\"roughguide\"/> ''[[Gjurm\u00ebt]]'' is one of the most famous and influential 1980s [[Albanian rock|rock]] bands from [[Pristina]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.albhitee.net/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-07-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629231409/http://albhitee.net/ |archive-date=2016-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Rock ===\n{{main|Rock music in Albania}}\n\n[[Rock music|Rock]] arrived in Albania, particularly in [[Kosovo]], in 1950 with an American and British influence. The first distinctively Albanian rock band was Blue Star founded in [[Pristina]]. \n{{Clear}}\n\n== Classical music ==\n\n=== Opera ===\n\n[[File:Fan Stilian Noli.jpg|thumb|right|[[Fan S. Noli]] <br /> {{small|1882\u20141965}}]]\n\n[[Palok\u00eb Kurti]] is usually said to be among the founders of Albanian opera.<ref name=\"cmoa\">{{cite web|title=Classical Music in Albania|url=http://frosina.org/classical-music-in-albania/|website=frosina.org|language=English}}</ref> Composer and priest, Martin Gjoka is also considered to be one of the most important founders of Albanian classical music.<ref name=\"cmoa\"/> Gjoka is said to be the first Albanian musician who showed great interest in traditional Albanian folk music considerably that of the deep [[Geography of Albania#Topography and hydrography|mountainous areas]] of the [[Northern Mountain Range (Albania)|north]] of Albania that was less influenced by foreign music.<ref name=\"cmoa\"/><ref name=\"frosina\">{{cite web|work=Frosina Information Network|title=The Tradition of Classical Music In Albania|url=http://www.frosina.org/about/infobits.asp?id=136|accessdate=28 August 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051017030453/http://www.frosina.org/about/infobits.asp?id=136|archivedate=17 October 2005}}</ref> During his lifetime, he composed several vocal and instrumental music using elements of urban art song and the folk melodies of the north.\n\nIn the 19th and 20th century, [[Fan S. Noli]] and [[Mikel Koliqi]] contributed to the development of classical music culture in Albania. They achieved prominence, with Noli using urban folk songs in his ''[[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] Overture'' and is also known for a symphonic poem called ''[[Gjergj Kastriot Scanderbeg|Scanderberg]]''.<ref name=\"koco\"/> Koliqi spent much of his life in prison for his religious beliefs, but managed to compose [[melodrama]]s such as ''[[Siege of Shkodra (1474)|The Siege of Shkod\u00ebr]]'', ''The Red Scarf'' and ''[[Rozafa Castle|Rozafa]]''.\n\nOther pivotal composers in modern Albanian classical music were Thoma Nassi, [[Kristo Kono]], Frano Ndoja and Lec Kurti who composed \"Arbereshja\" in 1915. \n[[Prenk Jakova]] became well known for operas including ''Scanderbeg'' and ''Mrika'', which were influenced by traditional [[Italian opera]], the [[belcanto]] style and Albanian folk music. [[\u00c7esk Zadeja]] composed in many styles, from symphonies to ballets, beginning in 1956, and also helped found the Music Conservatory of Tirana, the Theatre of Opera and Ballet, and the Assembly of Songs and Dances.<ref name=\"frosina\"/>\n\nLater in the middle of the 20th century, Albanian composers came to focus on [[ballet]]s, opera and other styles; these included [[Tonin Harapi]], [[Tish Daija]], [[Nikolla Zoraqi]], Thoma Gaqi, [[Feim Ibrahimi]], Shp\u00ebtim Kushta and many others. Since the [[Fall of communism in Albania|fall of the communism]] in Albania in the 21st century, composers like [[Aleksand\u00ebr Pe\u00e7i]], ethnologist musician [[Ramadan Sokoli]], Sokol Shup, Endri Sina, P\u00ebllumb Vorpsi and [[Vasil Tole]] have arisen, as have new music institutions like the Society of Music Professionals and the Society of New Albanian Music.<ref name=\"frosina\"/>\n\nThe contemporary opera artists such as [[Inva Mula]], [[Ermonela Jaho]] and [[Saimir Pirgu]] have achieved international recognition for their music.\n\n==Contemporary music==\n[[File:Ardit Gjebrea KM2009.jpg|thumb|left|190px|Noted singer and entertainer [[Ardit Gjebrea]] founded the [[K\u00ebnga Magjike]] festival in 1999.]]\n{{Main|Festivali i K\u00ebng\u00ebs|K\u00ebnga Magjike}}\n{{See also|Albanian rock|Albanian hip hop}}\nIn Albania, the most prominent rock bands and individuals only appeared after 1990 as rock music was prohibited. However, youth groups found ways to listen it through clandestine channels.<ref>Miranda Vickers, James Pettifer: [https://books.google.com/books?id=mnTCPH_ZGW4C&pg=PA299&dq=albanian+rock#v=onepage&q=albanian%20rock&f=false Albania: from anarchy to a Balkan identity], page 121 \"...in the 1970s Beatles songs could only be heard in clandestine condition...\"</ref>\n\nFurthermore, electronic music has become a mainstream music genre in Albania. Albanian artists and renowned DJs such as DJ Aldo, Vin Veli, DJ Sardi, Dj Tedd and others are successfully collaborating mainly with Italian and Romanian artists, while showcasing themselves in renown clubs in Tirana and in annual music festivals along the [[Albanian Riviera]] such as Turtle Fest and Soundwave Albania.\n{{Clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Music of Albania}}\n* [[:Category:Albanian singers|Albanian singers]]\n* [[Albanians]]\n* [[Culture of Albania]]\n* [[Music of Kosovo]] \n* [[List of Albanian musicians]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{citation|author=Arbatsky, Yuri|year=1953|title=Beating the Tupan in the Central Balkans |publisher=The Newbery Library}}\n*{{citation|last=Ko\u00e7o|first=Eno|title=Albanian urban lyric song in the 1930s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oWL2ZKPimKEC&pg=PA252|year=2004|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-4890-0}}\n*{{citation|last=Sugarman|first= Jane C.|year=1997|title=Engendering Song: Singing and Subjectivity at Prespa Albanian Weddings|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=0-226-77973-4}}\n* [http://upetd.up.ac.za/thesis/available/etd-08172011-150502/unrestricted/dissertation.pdf Mahony, Marinela. \"An Investigation of the Polyphonic Folk Music of Albania\". Dissertation. University of Pretoria, Pretoria: 2011.]\n* Rice, Timothy; Porter, James and Chris Goertzen. \"Albanian Music [by] Jane Sugarman.\" ''The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music Online'' 8, 2000: 986-1004.\n* Taylor, Roger. Review of \"The Music of Albania\". ''Brio'' 32, 1995: 40-42\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120405223217/http://www.newsound.org.rs/clanci_eng/7.%20Milto%20Vako.pdf Vako, Milto. \"The Origin and Development of Albanian Choral Music.\" ''New Sound: International Magazine for Music'' 28 2006.]\n*''Kenge, Albanian Piano Music'', Vol. 1, Kirsten Johnson, piano, Guild GMCD 7257.\n*''Rapsodi, Albanian Piano Music'', Vol. 2, Kirsten Johnson, piano, Guild GMCD 7300.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ville-ge.ch/meg/public_ph.php?id=HR1085-1/1 Audio clip: traditional Albanian music.]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Mus\u00e9e d'ethnographie de Gen\u00e8ve]]. Accessed November 25, 2010.\n* [http://www.isopolifonia.com Isopolyphony Official Website]\n* [http://www.radioemigranti.com Radio Emigranti \u2013 Albanian Traditional Music Radio Station]\n* [http://www.predavatel.com/mk/play/mrt_radio3_live Radio Skopje 3 Live Streaming - Skopje, Macedonia]\n* [http://tunein.com/tuner/?StationId=8031& Radio Tirana International Service LIVE]{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Music of Europe}}\n{{Music of Southeastern Europe (the Balkans)}}\n{{Albania topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Music Of Albania}}\n[[Category:Albanian music| ]]\n[[Category:Southern European music]]\n", "name_user": "Zoozaz1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInstrumentation:unorphaned article, added hyperlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music_of_Albania"}
{"title_page": "Sam Cronin", "text_new": "{{short description|American infernal soccer player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Sam Cronin\n| image                = Sam Cronin - MN UNited - MLS (35728038595) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size           = \n| caption              = Cronin playing for Minnesota United FC in 2017\n| fullname             = Sam Cronin<ref>{{Cite web|title=S. Cronin|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/sam-cronin/73581/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|1986|12|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place          = [[Atlanta, Georgia]], United States\n| height               = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| position             = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub          = \n| clubnumber           = \n| collegeyears1        = 2005\u20132008\n| college1             = [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's soccer|Wake Forest Demon Deacons]]\n| years1               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1               = [[Carolina Dynamo]]\n| caps1                = 39\n| goals1               = 9\n| years2               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs2               = [[Toronto FC]]\n| caps2                = 33\n| goals2               = 1\n| years3               = 2010\u20132014\n| clubs3               = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n| caps3                = 140\n| goals3               = 5\n| years4               = 2015\u20132017\n| clubs4               = [[Colorado Rapids]]\n| caps4                = 62\n| goals4               = 2\n| years5               = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs5               = [[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]]\n| caps5                = 18\n| goals5               = 0\n| nationalyears1       = 2009\n| nationalteam1        = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 2\n| nationalgoals1       = 0\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Country|{{USA}}}} \n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]|[[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2009]]}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Soccer]]}}\n| club-update          = November 4, 2018\n| ntupdate             = July 26, 2009\n}}\n\n'''Sam Cronin''' (born December 12, 1986) is an American former [[Association football|soccer]] player who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\n==Club career==\n===College and amateur===\nBorn in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], Cronin attended [[Mount Tabor High School]] in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]] where he moved with his family in 1999. He played [[college soccer]] at [[Wake Forest University]],<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=[[News & Record (Greensboro)|News & Record]]|first=Rob|last=Daniels|title=Wake soccer team wins with a Tar Heel flavor|url=http://www.news-record.com/node/10144|date=2007-12-14|access-date=2009-02-09|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120903180426/http://www.news-record.com/node/10144|archive-date=2012-09-03|df=}}</ref> scoring ten goals in twenty-four appearances in 2008, and was one of three finalists for the [[Hermann Trophy]], an award for the best [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] college soccer player.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=[[Soccer America]]|title=AWARDS: Cronin and Wake duo are Hermann finalists|url=http://www.socceramerica.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=30178|date=2008-12-15|access-date=2009-02-08|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120910050600/http://www.socceramerica.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=30178|archive-date=2012-09-10|df=}}</ref> Cronin ultimately finished as second runner-up for the trophy,<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Missouri Athletic Club]] |title=News Release: Kerri Hanks, Marcus Tracy Win Missouri Athletic Club's Hermann Trophy |url=http://www.mac-hermann-trophy.org/Banquet08/MAC%20Hermann%20Winners08.pdf |format=PDF |date=2009-01-09 |access-date=2009-02-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720142147/http://www.mac-hermann-trophy.org/Banquet08/MAC%20Hermann%20Winners08.pdf |archive-date=July 20, 2011 }}</ref> but won the 2008 [[Lowe's Senior CLASS Award]] for Men's Soccer.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]|title=Wake Forest: Cronin Named Semifinalist for Lowe's Senior CLASS Award|url=https://www.ncaa.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/091708abd.html|date=2008-09-17|accessdate=2009-02-08}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=The ACC|title=Sam Cronin Wins Lowe's Senior CLASS Award|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/121608aaa.html|date=2008-12-12|access-date=2009-02-09|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307214957/http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/121608aaa.html|archive-date=2012-03-07|df=}}</ref>\n\nDuring his college years, Cronin also played in the [[USL Premier Development League]] for [[Carolina Dynamo]], making thirty-nine appearances in four years, and scoring nine goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/docs/home/PDL-MLS09DraftList.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-11-26 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610163902/http://www.uslsoccer.com/docs/home/PDL-MLS09DraftList.pdf |archive-date=2011-06-10 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\n[[File:Sam Cronin.jpg|thumb|left|Cronin playing for San Jose Earthquakes in 2012]]\nCronin was selected second overall by [[Major League Soccer]] team [[Toronto FC]] in the [[2009 MLS SuperDraft]] on January 15, 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Toronto FC picks 2 Canadians in MLS draft|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/story/2009/01/15/mls-draft.html|date=2009-01-15|accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref> Cronin made his professional debut on 21 March 2009, in Toronto's first game of the 2009 MLS season against [[Kansas City Wizards]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Cole |last=Young |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |title=Toronto knocks off Wizards 3\u20132 |url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/story/1099872.html |date=2009-03-21 |access-date=2009-03-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325091249/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/story/1099872.html |archive-date=March 25, 2009 }}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on June 13, 2009 against the [[New York Red Bulls]].\n\nCronin was traded to [[San Jose Earthquakes]] on June 21, 2010 in return for allocation money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjearthquakes.com/news/2010/06/quakes-acquire-cronin-toronto-fc|title=Quakes Acquire Cronin from Toronto FC|date=21 June 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 19, 2015, Cronin was traded to [[Colorado Rapids]] in exchange for allocation money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradorapids.com/post/2015/01/19/sam-cronin-makes-switch-quakes-colorado-rapids|title=Sam Cronin makes the switch from the Quakes to Colorado Rapids|date=19 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>  He was selected as a member of the [[2015 MLS All-Star Game]], coming on at the start of the 2nd half, before being subbed off for [[Jozy Altidore]] in the 77th minute.  Cronin served as the Rapids team captain.\n\nOn March 31, 2017, Cronin was acquired by [[Minnesota United FC]] through the MLS waiver order. Minnesota traded a third-round pick in the [[2019 MLS SuperDraft]] to [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] to acquire Chicago's #1 pick in the waiver order in order to secure Cronin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnufc.com/post/2017/03/31/mnufc-adds-veteran-talent|title=MNUFC Adds Veteran Talent|date=31 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, Minnesota bought out the remainder of Cronin's contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=MNUFC Finalizes 2019 Roster |url=https://www.mnufc.com/post/2019/03/01/mnufc-finalizes-2019-rostert |publisher=Minnesota United |date=March 1, 2019|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn June 2009, he received his first call-up by the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] for the [[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. On July 11 Cronin made his debut with the United States against [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]], lending a hand in the opening goal in the 2\u20132 draw.\n\n==Honors==\n;Wake Forest University\n*[[NCAA Men's Division I Soccer Championship]]: [[2007 Division I Men's College Cup|2007]]\n\n;Toronto FC\n*[[Canadian Championship]] (2): [[2009 Canadian Championship|2009]], [[2010 Canadian Championship|2010]]\n\n;San Jose Earthquakes\n*[[Supporters' Shield]]: [[2012 Major League Soccer season|2012]]\n\n==Career stats<ref>{{cite web|title=MLS Players: Sam Cronin|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/players/sam-cronin|website=MLS Soccer|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align: center width=75%\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=10%| '''Team'''\n!rowspan=2 width=7%| '''Season'''\n!rowspan=2 width=7%| '''League'''\n!colspan=3 width=10%| Domestic<br/>League\n!colspan=3 width=10%| Domestic<br/>Playoffs\n!colspan=3 width=10%| Domestic<br/>Cup<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=3 width=10%| Concacaf<br/>Competition<sup>2</sup>\n!colspan=3 width=10%| Total\n|-\n!align=center| '''Apps'''\n!align=center| '''Goals'''\n!align=center| '''Assists'''\n!align=center| '''Apps'''\n!align=center| '''Goals'''\n!align=center| '''Assists'''\n!align=center| '''Apps'''\n!align=center| '''Goals'''\n!align=center| '''Assists'''\n!align=center| '''Apps'''\n!align=center| '''Goals'''\n!align=center| '''Assists'''\n!align=center| '''Apps'''\n!align=center| '''Goals'''\n!align=center| '''Assists'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=center|[[Toronto FC]]\n|align=center|2009\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|27\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|0\n!align=center|'''32'''\n!align=center|'''1'''\n!align=center|'''3'''\n|-\n|align=center|2010\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n!align=center|'''9'''\n!align=center|'''0'''\n!align=center|'''1'''\n|-\n|rowspan=5 align=center|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|align=center|2010\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n|align=center|-\n!align=center|'''14'''\n!align=center|'''0'''\n!align=center|'''0'''\n|-\n|align=center|2011\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|27\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|2\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n!align=center|'''27'''\n!align=center|'''0'''\n!align=center|'''2'''\n|-\n|align=center|2012\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|31\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n!align=center|'''33'''\n!align=center|'''1'''\n!align=center|'''6'''\n|-\n|align=center|2013\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|34\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|4\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n!align=center|'''34'''\n!align=center|'''2'''\n!align=center|'''4'''\n|-\n|align=center|2014\n|align=center|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|align=center|31\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|0\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center| \u2013\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n|align=center|\n!align=center|'''31'''\n!align=center|'''2'''\n!alig