         = \n| clubnumber           = \n| collegeyears1        = 2005\u20132008\n| college1             = [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons men's soccer|Wake Forest Demon Deacons]]\n| years1               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1               = [[Carolina Dynamo]]\n| caps1                = 39\n| goals1               = 9\n| years2               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs2               = [[Toronto FC]]\n| caps2                = 33\n| goals2               = 1\n| years3               = 2010\u20132014\n| clubs3               = [[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n| caps3                = 140\n| goals3               = 5\n| years4               = 2015\u20132017\n| clubs4               = [[Colorado Rapids]]\n| caps4                = 62\n| goals4               = 2\n| years5               = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs5               = [[Minnesota United FC|Minnesota United]]\n| caps5                = 18\n| goals5               = 0\n| nationalyears1       = 2009\n| nationalteam1        = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 2\n| nationalgoals1       = 0\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Country|{{USA}}}} \n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]|[[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2009]]}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Soccer]]}}\n| club-update          = November 4, 2018\n| ntupdate             = July 26, 2009\n}}\n\n'''Sam Cronin''' (born December 12, 1986) is an American former [[Association football|soccer]] player who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\n==Club career==\n===College and amateur===\nBorn in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], Cronin attended [[Mount Tabor High School]] in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]] where he moved with his family in 1999. He played [[college soccer]] at [[Wake Forest University]],<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=[[News & Record (Greensboro)|News & Record]]|first=Rob|last=Daniels|title=Wake soccer team wins with a Tar Heel flavor|url=http://www.news-record.com/node/10144|date=2007-12-14|access-date=2009-02-09|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120903180426/http://www.news-record.com/node/10144|archive-date=2012-09-03|df=}}</ref> scoring ten goals in twenty-four appearances in 2008, and was one of three finalists for the [[Hermann Trophy]], an award for the best [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] college soccer player.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=[[Soccer America]]|title=AWARDS: Cronin and Wake duo are Hermann finalists|url=http://www.socceramerica.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=30178|date=2008-12-15|access-date=2009-02-08|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120910050600/http://www.socceramerica.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=30178|archive-date=2012-09-10|df=}}</ref> Cronin ultimately finished as second runner-up for the trophy,<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Missouri Athletic Club]] |title=News Release: Kerri Hanks, Marcus Tracy Win Missouri Athletic Club's Hermann Trophy |url=http://www.mac-hermann-trophy.org/Banquet08/MAC%20Hermann%20Winners08.pdf |format=PDF |date=2009-01-09 |access-date=2009-02-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720142147/http://www.mac-hermann-trophy.org/Banquet08/MAC%20Hermann%20Winners08.pdf |archive-date=July 20, 2011 }}</ref> but won the 2008 [[Lowe's Senior CLASS Award]] for Men's Soccer.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]|title=Wake Forest: Cronin Named Semifinalist for Lowe's Senior CLASS Award|url=https://www.ncaa.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/091708abd.html|date=2008-09-17|accessdate=2009-02-08}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|publisher=The ACC|title=Sam Cronin Wins Lowe's Senior CLASS Award|url=http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/121608aaa.html|date=2008-12-12|access-date=2009-02-09|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307214957/http://www.theacc.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/121608aaa.html|archive-date=2012-03-07|df=}}</ref>\n\nDuring his college years, Cronin also played in the [[USL Premier Development League]] for [[Carolina Dynamo]], making thirty-nine appearances in four years, and scoring nine goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/docs/home/PDL-MLS09DraftList.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-11-26 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610163902/http://www.uslsoccer.com/docs/home/PDL-MLS09DraftList.pdf |archive-date=2011-06-10 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\n[[File:Sam Cronin.jpg|thumb|left|Cronin playing for San Jose Earthquakes in 2012]]\nCronin was selected second overall by [[Major League Soccer]] team [[Toronto FC]] in the [[2009 MLS SuperDraft]] on January 15, 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Toronto FC picks 2 Canadians in MLS draft|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/story/2009/01/15/mls-draft.html|date=2009-01-15|accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref> Cronin made his professional debut on 21 March 2009, in Toronto's first game of the 2009 MLS season against [[Kansas City Wizards]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Cole |last=Young |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |title=Toronto knocks off Wizards 3\u20132 |url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/story/1099872.html |date=2009-03-21 |access-date=2009-03-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325091249/http://www.kansascity.com/sports/story/1099872.html |archive-date=March 25, 2009 }}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on June 13, 2009 against the [[New York Red Bulls]].\n\nCronin was traded to [[San Jose Earthquakes]] on June 21, 2010 in return for allocation money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjearthquakes.com/news/2010/06/quakes-acquire-cronin-toronto-fc|title=Quakes Acquire Cronin from Toronto FC|date=21 June 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 19, 2015, Cronin was traded to [[Colorado Rapids]] in exchange for allocation money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradorapids.com/post/2015/01/19/sam-cronin-makes-switch-quakes-colorado-rapids|title=Sam Cronin makes the switch from the Quakes to Colorado Rapids|date=19 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>  He was selected as a member of the [[2015 MLS All-Star Game]], coming on at the start of the 2nd half, before being subbed off for [[Jozy Altidore]] in the 77th minute.  Cronin served as the Rapids team captain.\n\nOn March 31, 2017, Cronin was acquired by [[Minnesota United FC]] through the MLS waiver order. Minnesota traded a third-round pick in the [[2019 MLS SuperDraft]] to [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] to acquire Chicago's #1 pick in the waiver order in order to secure Cronin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnufc.com/post/2017/03/31/mnufc-adds-veteran-talent|title=MNUFC Adds Veteran Talent|date=31 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, Minnesota bought out the remainder of Cronin's contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=MNUFC Finalizes 2019 Roster |url=https://www.mnufc.com/post/2019/03/01/mnufc-finalizes-2019-rostert |publisher=Minnesota United |date=March 1, 2019|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn June 2009, he received his first call-up by the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] for the [[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. On July 11 Cronin made his debut with the United States against [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]], lending a hand in the opening goal in the 2\u20132 draw.\n\n==Honors==\n;Wake Forest University\n*[[NCAA Men's Division I Soccer Championship]]: [[2007 Division I Men's College Cup|2007]]\n\n;Toronto FC\n*[[Canadian Championship]] (2): [[2009 Canadian Championship|2009]], [[2010 Canadian Championship|2010]]\n\n;San Jose Earthquakes\n*[[Supporters' Shield]]: [[2012 Major League Soccer season|2012]]\n\n==Career stats<ref>{{cite web|title=MLS Players: Sam Cronin|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/players/sam-cronin|website=MLS Soccer|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align: center width=75%\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=10%|